{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478233"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:11:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:11:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17194"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17194"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.02,0.62,0.02,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9884"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108415"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9884"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17194"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90805"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4259"},{"type":"tags","id":"4272"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23204"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40643"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108415"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department after pulling a pot of boiling water onto himself 20 minutes ago. His parent reports the water spilled over his chest and abdomen. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed and crying. His pulse rate is 150/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. There are deep burns with white leathery appearance to his anterior chest and abdomen, with no blanching or capillary refill. The affected area is insensate to touch. The estimated total body surface area affected is 18%. There are no burns to his face or airways. His hands have blisters, red and painful to touch.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transfer immediately to burns unit","Give oral paracetamol","Commence intravenous fluid resuscitation","Apply silver sulfadiazine cream","Cool the burn with ice water"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with features consistent with third-degree (full thickness) burns, characterised by a white leathery appearance, insensate skin, and lack of blanching or capillary refill. With 18% total body surface area affected, there is significant risk of hypovolaemic shock. Children have thinner skin and burns can evolve over the first 48-72 hours thus it is essential for diligent initial examination and repeat reviews of the burns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous fluid resuscitation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step in management for burns more than 10% TBSA. The modified Parkland formula (3 mL/kg/%TBSA of Hartmann\u0027s solution over 24 hours, with half given in the first 8 hours) should be used to guide initial fluid requirements. Children are particularly susceptible to shock due to their smaller circulating blood volume.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to burns unit\u003C/strong\u003E, while necessary, should occur after initial stabilisation and fluid resuscitation have commenced. As per the RCH guidelines below burns requiring specialist burns unit referral in children include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGreater than 10% TBSA\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll full thickness burns\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpecial areas: face, ears, eyes, neck, hands, feet, genitalia, perineum or major joints\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECircumferential burns\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChemical or electrical burns\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBurns associated with trauma and/or spinal cord injury\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll inhalation/airway burns\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBurns in children under 12 months of age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECases beyond the comfort level of the treating hospital\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESilver sulfadiazine cream\u003C/strong\u003E can be used for wound management in burns but is not the priority in the acute setting. Fluid resuscitation takes precedence over wound care in large burns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral paracetamol\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be inadequate for pain control in severe burns. Additionally, establishing IV access for fluid resuscitation allows for appropriate parenteral analgesia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECooling with ice water\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated as it can cause tissue damage and hypothermia, particularly in young children. If cooling is performed, it should be with running cool (not cold) water for 20 minutes maximum, and only for small burns.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Third-degree burns require immediate fluid resuscitation using the modified Parkland formula (4 mL/kg/%TBSA of Hartmann\u0027s solution over 24 hours).","Burns greater than 10% total body surface area in children require specialist burn centre referral.","Full thickness burns, special areas (face, hands, feet, genitalia), and children under 12 months always require specialist burns unit referral."],"references":["Royal Children Hospital. Burns- Acute Management. Royal Children Hospital Clinical Practice Guidelines. 2020. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/burns/","World Health Organization. Burn Management. World Health Organization. Available at: https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/integrated-health-services-%28ihs%29/csy/surgical-care/imeesc-toolkit/best-practice-safety-protocols/burn-management.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90805"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17194"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90805"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-10T21:02:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-10T21:03:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9884"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108415"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","i